04630nam a22005655i 9780822383321DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20022001ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223833217 a10.1515/97808223833212doi  a(DE-B1597)553951  a(OCoLC)1027517583  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 7aSOC0260002bisacsh04a980.03/31 aSantiago, Silviano, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Space In-Between :bEssays on Latin American Culture /cSilviano Santiago; ed. by Fredric Jameson. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2002] 4c©2001  a1 online resource (200 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aLatin America in Translation : 2800tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction: Silviano Santiago, a Voice In-Between -- t1. Why and For What Purpose Does the European Travel? -- t2. Latin American Discourse: The Space In-Between -- t3. Eça, Author of Madame Bovary -- t4. Universality in Spite of Dependency -- t5. The Rhetoric of Verisimilitude -- t6. Worth Its Weight: Brazilian Modernist Fiction -- t7. The Permanence of the Discourse of Tradition in Modernism -- t8. Repression and Censorship in the Field of the Arts during the 1970s -- t9. Literature and Mass Culture -- t10. The Postmodern Narrator -- t11. Worldly Appeal: Local and Global Politics in the Shaping of Brazilian Culture -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSilviano Santiago has been a pioneer in the development of concepts crucial to the discourse of contemporary critical and cultural theory, especially postcolonial theory. The notions of “hybridity” and “the space in-between” have been so completely absorbed into current theory that few scholars even realize these terms began with Santiago. He was the first to introduce poststructuralist thought to Brazil—via his publication of the Glossario de Derrida and his role as a prominent teacher. The Space In-Between translates many of his seminal essays into English for the first time and, in the process, introduces the thought of one of Brazil’s foremost critics and theorists of the late twentieth century.Santiago’s work creates a theoretical field that transcends both the study of a specific national literature and the traditional perspectives of comparative literature. He examines the pedagogical and modernizing mission of Western voyagers from the conquistadors to the present. He deconstructs the ideas of “original” and “copy,” unpacking their implications for the notions of so-called dominant and dominated cultures. Santiago also confronts questions of cultural dependency and analyzes the problems involved in the imposition of an alien European history, the cultural displacements experienced by the Indians through their religious conversion, and the hierarchical suppression of native and Afro-Brazilian values.Elegantly written and translated, The Space In-Between will provide insights and perspectives that will interest cultural and literary theorists, postcolonial scholars, and other students of contemporary culture.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh1 aBurns, Tom.1 aGazzola, Ana Lucia.1 aJameson, Fredric, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aWilliams, Gareth.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822383321zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822383321423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780822383321/original  a978-3-11-071183-7  Duke University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_DUK_ALL